<div class="dablink">For software that creates a virtualized environment between the computer platform and its operating system, see <a href="/wiki/Virtual_machine" title="Virtual machine">Virtual machine</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:OpenSUSELinuxVD.png" class="image" title="OpenSUSE 10.2's implementation of virtual desktops with Desktop Effects."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a2/OpenSUSELinuxVD.png/250px-OpenSUSELinuxVD.png" width="250" height="156" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:OpenSUSELinuxVD.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/OpenSUSE" title="OpenSUSE">OpenSUSE</a> 10.2's implementation of virtual desktops with Desktop Effects.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>virtual desktop</b> is a term used, usually within the <a href="/wiki/WIMP_(computing)" title="WIMP (computing)">WIMP</a> paradigm, to describe ways in which a <a href="/wiki/Computer" title="Computer">computer</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Desktop_environment" title="Desktop environment">desktop environment</a> is expanded through the use of software.</p>
